SIMPLE: replenish
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Replenish
<hw>Re*plen"ish</hw> <pr>(r?-pl?n"?sh)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Replenished</conjf>
<pr>(-?sht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Replenishing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>replenissen</ets>,
OF. <ets>replenir</ets>; L. pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>plenus</ets>
full. See <er>Full</er>, <er>-ish</er>, and cf. <er>Replete</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To fill again after having been diminished or emptied;
to stock anew; hence, to fill completely; to cause to abound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Multiply and <qex>replenish</qex> the earth.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i.
28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The waters thus⟦br⟧
With fish <qex>replenished</qex>, and the air with fowl.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To finish; to complete; to perfect.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We smothered⟦br⟧
The most <qex>replenished</qex> sweet work of nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Replenish</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Replenish
<hw>Re*plen"ish</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To recover former
fullness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The humors will not <qex>replenish</qex> so soon.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Replenisher</ent>⟦br⟧
